### Summary (w/c 10.11.2025)

**Slower OV growth in W11 (+1% WoW), with GTV \+2% WoW exceeding the Â£200k threshold for the first time\! Our platform penetration (orders in FTT zones during window) continues to increase to 2.48% (+0.07ppt WoW).** 

[***Proposition Performance:***](#bookmark=kix.sut86zadyay) 

* FTT traffic (users exposed to the FTT proposition[^1]) and FTT engagement (proxied by collection page visits) have been on a downward trajectory since wc 19/10 \- likely driven in large part by the homepage XP launch on 23/10.  
* Despite this, engagement signals remain strong:  
  * Conversion from FTT traffic, FTT engagement and FTT entry points continues to rise, indicating that the proposition is resonating more as users become familiar with it.  
  * Returning-to-FTT cx and OV are up WoW: they accounted for 41% of cx this week (vs 37% last week), and 43% of OV this week (vs 40% last week).  
  * Ratings have improved vs this time last week (4.35 vs 4.28), though they remain below their peak and should continue to be monitored and addressed.  
* Other indicators remain steady:  
  * Scheduled orders are flat; top-performing brands, cuisines, and dishes remain consistent; and new-to-Roo, new-to-brand, family, and regional splits are all stable.  
  * High-frequency users continue to dominate: PLUS users account for 64% of cx (vs 66% last week), and 63% of FTT cx return to the platform within 7 days (vs 61% last week).  
* Next week will see the addition of \~100 new sites across existing zones, in an effort to **deepen selection**, focused on existing brands in UK and new brands in Ireland. This should help to step-change Cx engagement in zones with 3-5 sites currently), where conversion is \>10ppts weaker than zones with 6+ sites.

[***Marketing:***](#bookmark=kix.sxvabss8gggp) 

**Media Insights:** We continue to monitor channel performance weekly and make optimisations. In Steer Co next week (20/11) we will provide a more detailed in-campaign analysis view with a summary of performance and learnings to date. We have proceeded with the approved media upweight strategy putting increased budget behind our hero Sky partnership. 

Updates for this week:

* Aiming to have Sky partnership extension live next week as part of upweight.  
* To improve digital audio pacing weâ€™ve moved from two geotargeted radio ads to one,  
* Pacing in general has picked up across podcasts (following amendments to the investment over the mix of pods) and Sky in line with campaign expectation.  
* Q1 plan in progress as per recommended scenario \- here.

**CRM:** Day of the Week XP: â…“ of the audience received FT email and push on Sunday, Tuesday, and Thursday. Initial results show that FT email had a higher CTR and drove more orders on Tuesday (0.3% vs 0.2% Tue and Sun; 9 orders vs 0 and 7 on Sun, Thus). 

**DXGY:** Wave 1 entry ended 04/11. Since the launch of Wave 2 on 10/11, we have swept up an additional \+3.1k entrants, higher than that of any weekly performance for wave 1\. **Key Drivers**: 15.0k have entered in total, with 951 Cx completing all steps. To date, Â£23.9k vouchers have been earned, with spend at Â£13.1k (vs total budget Â£100k).

[***Operations Performance***](#bookmark=kix.jftpnmef9o8) ***and [Care:](#bookmark=kix.nm4yf4auhgge)*** 

**B10s:** 

* Highlights: OI dropped \-0.29ppt WoW to 2.95% compared to non-Dinneroo orders which dropped \-0.10ppt WoW to 1.86%. This helped increase Dinneroo App rating this week \+0.07pts WoW to 4.35. Only 28.69% of ratings were below 4 stars. Of those 4-star ratings 13% contained an OI, 10% contained RWT, and 14.7% contained an unacceptable lates.  
* Lowlights: Unacceptable lates rose for Dinneroo orders \+0.18ppt WoW to 10.53%, non-Dinneroo orders dropped \-0.98ppt WoW to 10.53%. This was contributed by RWT increasing for Dinneroo \+0.5ppt WoW to 6.90% and non-Dinneroo dropping \-0.30ppt WoW to 4.70%.   
* Escalation meeting held with Prezzo this morning to address OI, with commitment to exploring single-tray dishes, addressing â€˜missing potsâ€™ issue.

**Care:**

* **Claims:** increased vs prior week at 7.39% orders with a claim (+0.09 ppt WoW) and average claim amount at Â£15.41 (+45p WoW), reflecting poorer partner operational performance, with Missing Items remaining the top offender for CCPO at 21p, while Unacceptable Lates (15+ mins) increased to 3.27%.  
* **66p per Dinneroo order** (+11p WoW), which is **\+56p above [target](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1VI8MI8jZlmiXNNKKB_cWaeiW9eH3rQ-LK4Gbrv_FJsw/edit)** (10p) and **\+45p above budget** (21p).   
* Commercial focus on bundle improvements to address â€˜One Item Claimsâ€™ equalling Â£25, due to no modifiers. This is actively being explored by wagamama, Dishoom and Kricket \- our three largest contributors.

* **Cx Funnel \-** see [Appendix](#bookmark=kix.4uoy5466dy0l) for more detail  
  *  FTT traffic (users who have seen the FTT proposition) has been declining since wc 19/10. This appears to be driven in part by the [homepage XP launch](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1h5AV4b2PYUn7c0sRthyLFbzWbgPCJNKMlQjfXd8G8ew/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.8jnx6z27wc7d) (23/10) \- since wc 19/10 a significantly lower percentage of sessions see the mission tile entry point (75% this week vs 91% wc 19/10).   
  * With fewer users seeing FTT, engagement has also declined, evidenced by lower collection page traffic (a strong proxy for engagement, as most users navigate through the collection page), which follows a similar downward trend to overfall FTT traffic.

![][image1]![][image2]![][image3]

* Users who do see or engage with FTT are increasingly likely to convert: traffic-to-order and collection page-to-order rates are up, and conversion across all entry points has improved week-on-week (see [Appendix](#bookmark=kix.4uoy5466dy0l)).

![][image4]![][image3]

* Also noteworthy: the mission tile appears to be a declining driver of funnel entry \- this is likely due in part to (i) homepage XP (ii) pinning px carousel on home and (iii) reintroducing the pop up modalâ€¦ however it could also reflect cx fatigue with the tileâ€™s current name and imagery.

![][image5]

* **Order Composition**  
  * **Ordering patterns** \- scheduled orders are flat  
    * 19% scheduled (vs 19% last week)  
  * **Top performing brands, cuisines, dishes** \- top brands, cuisines and dishes remain constant  
    * Top 5 brands: Pho, Wagamama, Dishoom, PEX, Banana Tree (same as last week)  
    * Top cuisines: Asian dominates (53% vs 54% last week), followed by Indian (15% vs 15% last week) and Italian (12% vs 12% last week)  
    * Top 3 dishes: Wags Family Chicken Katsu, Phoâ€™s Pho the Whole Family and Dishoomâ€™s Chicken Ruby (same as last week)  
* **Cx Composition \-** New-to-Roo and new-to-brand are constant. OV continues to be driven by high-frequency users, with PLUS users maintaining dominance (though down vs last week) and almost 2/3rds of users returning to the platform within 7 days (up vs last week). Returning-to-FTT continues to grow from a cx and OV share perspective. From a demographic POV, family split and location split remain similar.   
  * **New-to-Roo Cx:** 1% cx are new-to-platform (vs 1% last week)  
  * **New-to-Brand Cx:**  34% of orders are new to brand (vs 34% last week, 37% week before)  
  * **PLUS / Frequent Cx:** 64% of orders are from PLUS users (vs 66% last week); 63% return to platform within 7 days (vs 61% last week)  
  * **Returning-to-FTT:** Returning-to-FTT cx and OV are up WoW: they accounted for 41% of cx this week (vs 37% last week), and 43% of OV this week (vs 40% last week).

![][image6]![][image7]

* **Family split:** 16% Families per LBDS (vs 16% last week)  
  * **Location:** Similar to previous week: FTT OV composition by region closely aligns to total Roo GTV composition by region  
* **Cx Behaviour** \- Ratings have seen a modest uplift vs this time last week  
  * **Ratings:** Ratings are up vs this time last week (4.35 vs 4.28), though \- notably \- last weekâ€™s rating has increased to 4.42, suggesting that positive reviews often come in with a slight delay, while negative reviews appear more immediately. 1\* orders remain steady (8% vs 8% this time last week), while 5\* orders have increased (71% vs 69% this time last week)

#### B) CRM Performance Insights ([Lina Gallego](mailto:lina.gallego@deliveroo.co.uk)[Leon Man](mailto:leon.man@deliveroo.co.uk) ) 

**CRM:**   
**W/C 10 Nov:** We launched the Day of the Week experiment, where one-third of the audience receives FT email and push communications on Sunday, Tuesday, and Thursday at 12:00 p.m. and 12:30 p.m. respectively. Initial results indicate that the FT email performed best on Tuesday, achieving a higher CTR (0.3% vs. 0.2% on Sunday and Tuesday) and driving more orders (9 vs. 0 and 7 on Sunday and Thursday). Push performance remained consistent across days, with a CTR of 0.6%. Based on these findings, we donâ€™t recommend any changes to the FT CRM calendar at this stage.

This week we had an issue with Family Dinneroo Rewards journey (DXGY). Cx did not enter the journey due to an error encountered while building DXGY for Plus, both journeys use the same custom event, which caused the conflict. This issue has now been resolved. 

**W/C 17 Nov:** We are launching our first Px solus send this week. We are launching with wagamamas to an audience of \~1M cx. The remaining \~0.8M cx will receive a new inspiration email using our OOH imagery. Please see final creatives [Family Time Q4 CRM](https://docs.google.com/presentation/u/0/d/1LRtvJMjouG1LqwZObfJ1d_cNT_1S_vp53jWr9ze1oqs/edit). 

Continuous improvement: 

* Further targeting proposal \- exclude tribe segment â€œBig Brand Loyalistâ€ from email from w/c 17/11. We tested for two weeks sending to different tribes to understand CTR and FT conversion. Big Brand loyalist drove 0 orders at a CTR 0.1% for email. Segment size \~153K Cx.    
* Following up on feedback from last week, for the PX email launching on 24.11, we want to identify zones with more PX in the area, and communicate â€œNew in Family Dinnerooâ€ messaging.

For clarity, 28.69% of ratings were below 4 stars. Of those 4-star ratings 13% contained an OI, 10% contained RWT, and 14.7% contained an unacceptable late. Focus continues on decreasing OI and RWT issues.

#### A1) Whole Bundle Claims

Currently, due to bundle design, some of our top OV Partners such as wagamama, Dishoom and Kricket, are receiving whole bundle claims despite the contact reason being missing items, spilled or cooked incorrectly \- which is often only due to a single element of the bundle. With wagamama, this is hard to quantify as portion sizes are not clear, and they do not want to add confusion to their menu flow. This is actively being explored with Dishoom and Kricket in terms of adding elements of the bundle as mandatory bundle items.
